In the example given (Fig. 8) generally better surface qualities can be achieved with higher vibration frequency. The machining also results in drastically reduced tool wear achieving highest geometrical accuracies (Fig. 9
                           ). Also the chip breakage can be positively influenced by the vibration assistance (Fig. 10
                           ), resulting in favorable short or even discontinuous chips. Further advantages of vibration assisted cutting are the reduction of built-up edges during machining and the elimination of burrs on the workpiece side.
